Iu the present volume an attempt has been made to explain some portions ol Lucretius' De Rerum Natura. The entire poem is published for the reason that, being a work ol art, it ought to be presented as a whole. The first, third, and fifth books were chosen for comment because they contain the gist of the poet's doctrine, and a greater number ol fine passages than the others. lt is hoped that the reading of the remaining books will be· facilitated by the analysis of the subject-matter given in the Introduction. If the method ol annotating pursned in this volume meets with approval, an edition ol the whole poem will shortly appear.
